  'Which summary line best expresses the narrative function of 1 Samuel 2?',
  '["Hannah praises the LORD for overturning the proud and lifting the humble, setting the tone for the whole book. The chapter then contrasts her faith with the corruption of Eli''s sons, who abuse sacrifices and despise the LORD''s offering. Samuel grows before God while a man of God warns Eli that his house will be judged for dishonoring the sanctuary.", "Samuel hears the LORD calling in the night, and after Eli''s help he learns to answer, \"Speak, for your servant hears.\" The message confirms judgment on Eli''s house and cannot be hidden. Samuel grows into a trustworthy prophet whose words are established throughout Israel.", "Israel treats the ark like a talisman and marches it into battle, but the Philistines rout the army and capture the ark. Eli falls backward and dies when he hears the news, and his daughter-in-law names her son Ichabod because the glory has departed from Israel. The chapter is a stark warning that sacred objects cannot replace covenant faithfulness.", "The Philistines place the ark in Dagon''s temple, but Dagon falls before it and the people are struck with affliction. Town after town suffers because the ark brings the LORD''s presence into enemy territory. The chapter makes clear that the captured ark is not captive at all; it is still ruling."]'::jsonb,
  'Hannah praises the LORD for overturning the proud and lifting the humble, setting the tone for the whole book. The chapter then contrasts her faith with the corruption of Eli''s sons, who abuse sacrifices and despise the LORD''s offering. Samuel grows before God while a man of God warns Eli that his house will be judged for dishonoring the sanctuary.',
