  9,
  5,
  5,
  'What final perspective best fits 1 Samuel 5?',
  '["The Philistines place the ark in Dagon''s temple, but Dagon falls before it and the people are struck with affliction. Town after town suffers because the ark brings the LORD''s presence into enemy territory. The chapter makes clear that the captured ark is not captive at all; it is still ruling.", "The Philistines send the ark back on a new cart with guilt offerings, testing whether the plague came from God or chance. The cows head straight for Beth-shemesh, confirming that the LORD is guiding the return. Israel rejoices but also learns reverence when some men look into the ark and are struck down.", "Samuel anoints Saul, gives him signs, and tells him that the Spirit will come upon him as proof of God''s choice. Saul prophesies with the prophets, and the people marvel because the change is so unmistakable. Yet Saul also hides, hinting that his kingship will be marked by uncertainty as well as promise.", "When Nahash the Ammonite threatens Jabesh-gilead, Saul is moved by the Spirit and gathers Israel to rescue the city. The victory unites the tribes and confirms Saul''s public kingship at Gilgal. The chapter shows the best side of Saul: courage, mercy, and the ability to rally a divided people."]'::jsonb,
