  'What final perspective best fits 1 Samuel 11?',
  '["When Nahash the Ammonite threatens Jabesh-gilead, Saul is moved by the Spirit and gathers Israel to rescue the city. The victory unites the tribes and confirms Saul''s public kingship at Gilgal. The chapter shows the best side of Saul: courage, mercy, and the ability to rally a divided people.", "Samuel reviews his leadership, insists that he has taken no bribe, and reminds Israel how the LORD repeatedly rescued them from enemies. He warns that asking for a king does not remove accountability, and he calls both ruler and people to fear and serve the LORD. The speech closes the era of judges with a moral and spiritual summary.", "The LORD sends Samuel to Bethlehem to anoint a new king from Jesse''s sons, and David is chosen because the LORD looks on the heart. The Spirit comes upon David, while an evil spirit troubles Saul and leads to the introduction of David as a musician in the court. The chapter quietly begins the rise of Israel''s future king.", "David comes to the battlefield with bread for his brothers and ends up facing Goliath, the giant who mocks the armies of the living God. David declares that the battle belongs to the LORD, strikes Goliath with a sling stone, and wins a decisive victory with the giant''s own sword. The chapter celebrates faith that sees God''s honor where others see only impossible odds."]'::jsonb,
  'When Nahash the Ammonite threatens Jabesh-gilead, Saul is moved by the Spirit and gathers Israel to rescue the city. The victory unites the tribes and confirms Saul''s public kingship at Gilgal. The chapter shows the best side of Saul: courage, mercy, and the ability to rally a divided people.',
  'This final perspective fits 1 Samuel 11 (1 Samuel 11:1-11-1 Samuel 11:8-15).'
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
  SELECT 1 FROM quiz_question_bank
  WHERE book_number = 9
    AND chapter = 11
    AND difficulty_stage = 5
    AND prompt = 'What final perspective best fits 1 Samuel 11?'
);

