  'Which advanced summary best matches 1 Samuel 12?',
  '["Samuel reviews his leadership, insists that he has taken no bribe, and reminds Israel how the LORD repeatedly rescued them from enemies. He warns that asking for a king does not remove accountability, and he calls both ruler and people to fear and serve the LORD. The speech closes the era of judges with a moral and spiritual summary.", "When Nahash the Ammonite threatens Jabesh-gilead, Saul is moved by the Spirit and gathers Israel to rescue the city. The victory unites the tribes and confirms Saul''s public kingship at Gilgal. The chapter shows the best side of Saul: courage, mercy, and the ability to rally a divided people.", "Saul grows anxious when the Philistines mass and Samuel does not arrive on time, so he offers the burnt offering himself. Samuel rebukes him for acting foolishly and announces that his kingdom will not endure. The chapter marks the first clear break between Saul''s kingship and God''s enduring purpose.", "The LORD sends Samuel to Bethlehem to anoint a new king from Jesse''s sons, and David is chosen because the LORD looks on the heart. The Spirit comes upon David, while an evil spirit troubles Saul and leads to the introduction of David as a musician in the court. The chapter quietly begins the rise of Israel''s future king."]'::jsonb,
  'Samuel reviews his leadership, insists that he has taken no bribe, and reminds Israel how the LORD repeatedly rescued them from enemies. He warns that asking for a king does not remove accountability, and he calls both ruler and people to fear and serve the LORD. The speech closes the era of judges with a moral and spiritual summary.',
