  'What final perspective best fits 1 Samuel 14?',
  '["Jonathan and his armor bearer trust the LORD and spark a panic among the Philistines, showing that faith can win where armies hesitate. Saul''s rash oath, however, weakens the people and nearly costs Jonathan his life after the king''s own son tastes honey. The chapter contrasts brave initiative with foolish religion and ends with Saul''s damaged leadership.", "Samuel commands Saul to destroy Amalek completely, but Saul spares the best livestock and keeps King Agag alive. When confronted, Saul blames the people, but Samuel declares that obedience is better than sacrifice and that the LORD has rejected Saul as king. The chapter ends with Agag''s death and Samuel''s grief over Saul''s failure.", "Saul orders David killed, but Jonathan intercedes and briefly restores peace between them. When Saul''s rage returns, David escapes through a window and Michal helps him flee while pretending he is ill. The chapter shows how family ties and loyal friendship still cannot overcome Saul''s growing hostility.", "David and Jonathan use a secret sign at the feast to determine Saul''s intent, and Saul''s murderous anger is confirmed. The two friends renew their covenant and part with grief, knowing the kingdom''s conflict will separate them. The chapter deepens the tragedy by showing loyalty trapped inside royal violence."]'::jsonb,
