  'Which summary line best expresses the narrative function of 1 Samuel 15?',
  '["Samuel commands Saul to destroy Amalek completely, but Saul spares the best livestock and keeps King Agag alive. When confronted, Saul blames the people, but Samuel declares that obedience is better than sacrifice and that the LORD has rejected Saul as king. The chapter ends with Agag''s death and Samuel''s grief over Saul''s failure.", "The LORD sends Samuel to Bethlehem to anoint a new king from Jesse''s sons, and David is chosen because the LORD looks on the heart. The Spirit comes upon David, while an evil spirit troubles Saul and leads to the introduction of David as a musician in the court. The chapter quietly begins the rise of Israel''s future king.", "David comes to the battlefield with bread for his brothers and ends up facing Goliath, the giant who mocks the armies of the living God. David declares that the battle belongs to the LORD, strikes Goliath with a sling stone, and wins a decisive victory with the giant''s own sword. The chapter celebrates faith that sees God''s honor where others see only impossible odds.", "Jonathan loves David as his own soul, and the two men form a covenant that lasts beyond politics. David succeeds in everything he does, which makes Saul jealous and afraid as the people''s praise shifts toward the young warrior. The chapter moves from friendship to rising royal tension."]'::jsonb,
  'Samuel commands Saul to destroy Amalek completely, but Saul spares the best livestock and keeps King Agag alive. When confronted, Saul blames the people, but Samuel declares that obedience is better than sacrifice and that the LORD has rejected Saul as king. The chapter ends with Agag''s death and Samuel''s grief over Saul''s failure.',
  'This summary line expresses the narrative function of 1 Samuel 15.'
