  '["The LORD sends Samuel to Bethlehem to anoint a new king from Jesse''s sons, and David is chosen because the LORD looks on the heart. The Spirit comes upon David, while an evil spirit troubles Saul and leads to the introduction of David as a musician in the court. The chapter quietly begins the rise of Israel''s future king.", "David comes to the battlefield with bread for his brothers and ends up facing Goliath, the giant who mocks the armies of the living God. David declares that the battle belongs to the LORD, strikes Goliath with a sling stone, and wins a decisive victory with the giant''s own sword. The chapter celebrates faith that sees God''s honor where others see only impossible odds.", "David arrives at Nob hungry and receives the holy bread and Goliath''s sword from Ahimelech, but the encounter later costs the priests their lives. He then flees to Gath, where he pretends madness to survive among the Philistines. The chapter shows David in exile, scrambling for food, weapons, and safety while Saul''s violence expands.", "David gathers a band of distressed followers in the cave of Adullam while Saul''s suspicion turns into murderous paranoia. Doeg tells Saul that Ahimelech helped David, and the king orders the priests of Nob killed, deepening the bloodguilt on his house. Abiathar escapes to David, linking the outlaw king and the surviving priesthood."]'::jsonb,
  'The LORD sends Samuel to Bethlehem to anoint a new king from Jesse''s sons, and David is chosen because the LORD looks on the heart. The Spirit comes upon David, while an evil spirit troubles Saul and leads to the introduction of David as a musician in the court. The chapter quietly begins the rise of Israel''s future king.',
  'This final perspective fits 1 Samuel 16 (1 Samuel 16:1-13-1 Samuel 16:14-23).'
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
