  'What final perspective best fits 1 Samuel 25?',
  '["Samuel dies, and David moves deeper into the wilderness where Nabal insults him and refuses food for his men. Abigail quickly intervenes with provisions, speaks humbly to David, and prevents bloodshed by reminding him that the LORD will fight his battles. Nabal later dies after his drunken feast, and David receives Abigail as wife, turning restraint into mercy and provision into peace.", "When Saul camps in the wilderness, David slips into the camp with Abishai and takes Saul''s spear and water jug instead of killing him. From a distance he calls Saul to account, and Saul again admits that he has sinned and that David will surely prevail. The second chance underlines David''s refusal to seize the throne by violence.", "While David and his men are away, Amalekites raid Ziklag, burn the city, and take the families captive. David strengthens himself in the LORD, pursues the raiders with divine guidance, and recovers everyone along with much spoil. The chapter ends with David sharing the recovered goods widely, showing both courage and generosity.", "The Philistines defeat Israel at Mount Gilboa, and Saul''s sons fall beside him. Wounded and unable to continue, Saul falls on his own sword after his armor bearer refuses to kill him, and the Philistines later display the bodies in shame. Men of Jabesh-gilead recover the remains and bury them with fasting, ending Saul''s reign in grief and honor."]'::jsonb,
  'Samuel dies, and David moves deeper into the wilderness where Nabal insults him and refuses food for his men. Abigail quickly intervenes with provisions, speaks humbly to David, and prevents bloodshed by reminding him that the LORD will fight his battles. Nabal later dies after his drunken feast, and David receives Abigail as wife, turning restraint into mercy and provision into peace.',
  'This final perspective fits 1 Samuel 25 (1 Samuel 25:1-3-1 Samuel 25:36-44).'
