  '["When Saul camps in the wilderness, David slips into the camp with Abishai and takes Saul''s spear and water jug instead of killing him. From a distance he calls Saul to account, and Saul again admits that he has sinned and that David will surely prevail. The second chance underlines David''s refusal to seize the throne by violence.", "David decides he will perish by Saul''s hand unless he finds refuge among the Philistines, so he settles in Ziklag under Achish. From there he raids surrounding peoples while telling Achish that he has struck Judah, keeping the king of Gath confident in his loyalty. The chapter captures David living by concealment and survival in enemy territory.", "The Philistines defeat Israel at Mount Gilboa, and Saul''s sons fall beside him. Wounded and unable to continue, Saul falls on his own sword after his armor bearer refuses to kill him, and the Philistines later display the bodies in shame. Men of Jabesh-gilead recover the remains and bury them with fasting, ending Saul''s reign in grief and honor.", "Hannah pours out her grief before the LORD at Shiloh and vows that if God gives her a son she will dedicate him to lifelong service. Eli misreads her silent prayer at first, then blesses her, and the LORD opens her womb. Samuel is born, weaned, and brought to the sanctuary as a living answer to prayer."]'::jsonb,
  'When Saul camps in the wilderness, David slips into the camp with Abishai and takes Saul''s spear and water jug instead of killing him. From a distance he calls Saul to account, and Saul again admits that he has sinned and that David will surely prevail. The second chance underlines David''s refusal to seize the throne by violence.',
