  '["While David and his men are away, Amalekites raid Ziklag, burn the city, and take the families captive. David strengthens himself in the LORD, pursues the raiders with divine guidance, and recovers everyone along with much spoil. The chapter ends with David sharing the recovered goods widely, showing both courage and generosity.", "The Philistines defeat Israel at Mount Gilboa, and Saul''s sons fall beside him. Wounded and unable to continue, Saul falls on his own sword after his armor bearer refuses to kill him, and the Philistines later display the bodies in shame. Men of Jabesh-gilead recover the remains and bury them with fasting, ending Saul''s reign in grief and honor.", "Hannah pours out her grief before the LORD at Shiloh and vows that if God gives her a son she will dedicate him to lifelong service. Eli misreads her silent prayer at first, then blesses her, and the LORD opens her womb. Samuel is born, weaned, and brought to the sanctuary as a living answer to prayer.", "Hannah praises the LORD for overturning the proud and lifting the humble, setting the tone for the whole book. The chapter then contrasts her faith with the corruption of Eli''s sons, who abuse sacrifices and despise the LORD''s offering. Samuel grows before God while a man of God warns Eli that his house will be judged for dishonoring the sanctuary."]'::jsonb,
  'While David and his men are away, Amalekites raid Ziklag, burn the city, and take the families captive. David strengthens himself in the LORD, pursues the raiders with divine guidance, and recovers everyone along with much spoil. The chapter ends with David sharing the recovered goods widely, showing both courage and generosity.',
  'This summary line expresses the narrative function of 1 Samuel 30.'
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
  SELECT 1 FROM quiz_question_bank
  WHERE book_number = 9
    AND chapter = 30
    AND difficulty_stage = 4
    AND prompt = 'Which summary line best expresses the narrative function of 1 Samuel 30?'
);

